The National Association of Sukur Association have made case for the creation of Sukur Chiefdom out of the Mubi Emirate Council in Admawa state. Dr Luka Njiling, spokesman for the group at a press briefing Friday in Yola said, the new chiefdom would enable the people  of the area enjoy status like other kingdoms in the country. Njiling said the urge was imperative, following the appointment of non-Sukur indigene as the District Head and the move to change the name of Sukur to Midlu. “There is no way that a migrant could be appointed the District Head of Sukur. “The appointment of non-Sukur as District Head of Sukur is repugnant to national justice and equity. “The move to remove the name ‘SUKUR’ from its history and give it another name is belligerent and futile attempt to rewrite history.” He called on government to be conscious of peace required to achieve its objectives. The group also harps for the restoration of leadership of the District to the right owner, whose father ruled the area for over 25 years. Mr Solomon Kumangar, Director General Media and Communications to government in his response, said a particular village which produced the last district, could not claim sole preserve of the District as their own. Kumangar said somebody should not for economic purpose play with the truth. He said the matter has nothing to do or temper with the tradition of the area. Sukur was listed into the prestigious UNESCO Heritage Site in 1999. 